etymologies: early 18th century; earliest use found in Prerogative of Primogeniture. From Hellenistic Greek and Byzantine Greek αὐτοκράτωρ title of the Roman emperor (rendering classical Latin imperātor; specific use of ancient Greek αὐτοκράτωρ one's own master, absolute ruler from αὐτο- + -κράτωρ), originally after Russian samoderžec absolute ruler, (now obsolete) sovereign ruler (Old Russian samod′rž′c′ master, sovereign ruler, absolute ruler), itself after Byzantine Greek αὐτοκράτωρ

notes.text: Chiefly with reference to Russian tsars, or to Roman and Byzantine emperors.
